TI  - [Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy complicating a prolonged corticotherapy for
      hemorrhagic rectocolitis].
PG  - 48-51
AB  - BACKGROUND: The cardiac side-effects of corticosteroid therapy are very uncommon.
      CASE REPORT: A girl with ulcerative colitis developed at the age of 8 years an
      acute digestive episode despite prednisolone and total parenteral nutrition. The 
      patient was then given intravenous methylprednisolone (2 mg/kg/d). Polypnea
      appeared 25 days later while blood pressure remained normal. Echocardiography
      revealed a cardiac hypertrophy associated with a systolic anterior motion of the 
      mitral valve. Cardiac symptoms and echography findings returned to normal after
      reduction of corticosteroid therapy and its administration via the oral route.
      CONCLUSION: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy has been described in preterms treated
      with dexamethasone for bronchopulmonary dysplasia. It is exceptional in older
      children under corticosteroid therapy and its mechanism remains unknown.
